    <item>
      <title>Logic and AI</title>
      <link>https://logicalmethods.ai/exercises/logic-and-ai/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://logicalmethods.ai/exercises/logic-and-ai/</guid>
      <description>&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;definitions&#34; &gt;&lt;h5 class=&#34;&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;d-inline-flex flex-row m-0  p-0 &#34;&gt;Definitions&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h5&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Note&lt;/em&gt;: A definition needs to fully explain the meaning of a concept. This is&#xA;typically done by saying under which precise conditions the concept applies.&#xA;That is, the answer should have the form like &amp;ldquo;A valid inference is an inference&#xA;such that&amp;hellip;&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;An inference is valid just in case &amp;hellip;&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;a-inference&#34; &gt;&lt;h6 class=&#34;&#34;&gt;a.) Inference&lt;/h6&gt;&lt;p&gt;Give a definition of inference. Include examples (where your definition applies)&#xA;and non-examples (where it does not). Make sure to explain why your definition&#xA;applies or not.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Valid inference</title>
      <link>https://logicalmethods.ai/exercises/valid-inference/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://logicalmethods.ai/exercises/valid-inference/</guid>
      <description>&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;deduction-and-induction&#34; &gt;&lt;h5 class=&#34;&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;d-inline-flex flex-row m-0  p-0 &#34;&gt;Deduction and Induction&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h5&gt;&lt;p&gt;Give an example of one for each of the following:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;a&#34; class=&#34; homework&#34;&gt;&lt;h6 class=&#34; homework&#34;&gt;a)&lt;/h6&gt;&lt;p&gt;A deductively valid inference&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;b&#34; &gt;&lt;h6 class=&#34;&#34;&gt;b)&lt;/h6&gt;&lt;p&gt;A deductively invalid inference&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;c&#34; &gt;&lt;h6 class=&#34;&#34;&gt;c)&lt;/h6&gt;&lt;p&gt;An inductively valid inference&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;d&#34; class=&#34; homework&#34;&gt;&lt;h6 class=&#34; homework&#34;&gt;d)&lt;/h6&gt;&lt;p&gt;An inductively invalid inference&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;monotonicity&#34; class=&#34; solved&#34;&gt;&lt;h5 class=&#34;solved&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;d-inline-flex flex-row m-0  p-0 &#34;&gt;Monotonicity&#xA;      &#xA;      &amp;nbsp;&#xA;      &lt;button &#xA;        class=&#34;btn p-0 m-0 border-0&#34; &#xA;        aria-expanded=&#34;false&#34;&#xA;        aria-controls=&#34;monotonicitySolution&#34;&#xA;        onclick=&#34;showPasswordModal(&#39;monotonicitySolution&#39;, &#39;exc-val&#39;)&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;i class=&#34;bi bi-lightbulb-fill&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/button&gt;&#xA;      &#xA;      &#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h5&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;a-deduction&#34; &gt;&lt;h6 class=&#34;&#34;&gt;a) Deduction&lt;/h6&gt;&lt;p&gt;Give an argument that if an inference is deductively valid, then adding&#xA;additional premises doesnâ€™t cancel the validity of the inference.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Formal languages</title>
      <link>https://logicalmethods.ai/exercises/formal-languages/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://logicalmethods.ai/exercises/formal-languages/</guid>
      <description>&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;bnfs&#34; class=&#34; solved&#34;&gt;&lt;h5 class=&#34;solved&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;d-inline-flex flex-row m-0  p-0 &#34;&gt;BNFs&#xA;      &#xA;      &amp;nbsp;&#xA;      &lt;button &#xA;        class=&#34;btn p-0 m-0 border-0&#34; &#xA;        aria-expanded=&#34;false&#34;&#xA;        aria-controls=&#34;bnfsSolution&#34;&#xA;        onclick=&#34;showPasswordModal(&#39;bnfsSolution&#39;, &#39;exc-for&#39;)&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;i class=&#34;bi bi-lightbulb-fill&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/button&gt;&#xA;      &#xA;      &#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h5&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div id=&#34;a&#34; class=&#34; homework&#34;&gt;&lt;h6 class=&#34; homework&#34;&gt;a)&lt;/h6&gt;&lt;p&gt;Consider the following propositional language, described informally:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;container &#34; &gt;&#xA;  &lt;figure&gt;&#xA;    &lt;blockquote class=&#34;blockquote fs-6&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;p&gt;&#xA;      We have three propositional variables $BLUE$, $GREEN$, and $RED$. Further, we&#xA;have the propositional connectives $\neg,\land, \lor$, which work as usual, i.e.&#xA;$\neg$ can be written in front of a formula to negate it, $\land$ can be written&#xA;between two formulas flanked by parentheses to conjoin them, and similarly for&#xA;$\lor$. Additionally, we have two unary modal operators $\square,\lozenge$, which can be&#xA;written in front of a formula to form a new formula.&#xA;      &lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
